{
  "ir_hash": "sha256:4283bbc26641486a074da6198b3eedc87db2ce1fd74e0fb63195e12b24cf2b18",
  "knowledges": [
    {
      "content": "A *coding agent* is an LLM-driven system whose task is to read, edit, and execute source code in pursuit of a user-specified software-engineering goal (bug fix, feature implementation, refactor, etc.). The *scaffold* of such an agent is the source-code-level harness that wraps the underlying LLM: the prompt-and-loop control flow, the set of callable tools, the memory / context-management discipline, and the agent's persistent state machine. Different open-source coding agents (Aider, OpenDevin, SWE-agent, Cline, moatless-tools, ...) instantiate this scaffold in materially different ways, and those differences are observable directly in the implementation source.",
      "content_hash": "d14e8cfcc5623c81541c2d58556bfd9713d591905d6bcd99c927a403690ff86c",
      "declaration_index": 0,
      "exported": false,
      "id": "github:2604_03515_scaffold_taxonomy::coding_agent_setting",
      "label": "coding_agent_setting",
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Coding-agent scaffold (formal setting)",
      "type": "setting"
    },
    {
      "content": "The study scope is a corpus of real-world open-source coding-agent implementations, examined at the source-code level. The reference implementation cited via the GitHub link is https://github.com/aorwall/moatless-tools; the taxonomy is derived by comparing scaffold designs across this and analogous projects rather than by running them on benchmarks.",
      "content_hash": "29fa965b047ea6172c3179a7d9491febca77d59e536824cda8cedbd36cee42e3",
      "declaration_index": 1,
      "exported": false,
      "id": "github:2604_03515_scaffold_taxonomy::study_scope",
      "label": "study_scope",
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Study population: open-source coding-agent source code",
      "type": "setting"
    },
    {
      "content": "The work delivers a **source-code taxonomy of coding-agent architectures** -- a structured classification of how coding agents are built, derived from inspection of their implementation source rather than from black-box behavioural evaluation.",
      "content_hash": "a419af1ef28cdfa133e0a0426f104283db025c429f967149b59fc5206deff70a",
      "declaration_index": 2,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_03515_scaffold_taxonomy::source_code_taxonomy_built",
      "label": "source_code_taxonomy_built",
      "metadata": {
        "prior": 0.93,
        "prior_justification": "Self-report of contribution in the abstract: the authors explicitly frame the work as a source-code taxonomy of coding-agent architectures. This is a methodological framing claim, not a quantitative result, and is directly verifiable by reading the paper. High prior.",
        "source": "artifacts/2604.03515-scaffold-taxonomy.md (abstract, sentence 1)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Source-code taxonomy of coding-agent architectures",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "The work **analyses real-world implementations to derive structural patterns** in how coding agents manage **context, tools, and state** -- i.e. the taxonomy categories are grounded in repeated design choices observed across multiple existing agent codebases, not synthesised top-down.",
      "content_hash": "64d2cf7bb91ee8808a7324b3698e448d0b7ef0e333f3e1ce9351681360257bef",
      "declaration_index": 3,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_03515_scaffold_taxonomy::structural_patterns_derived",
      "label": "structural_patterns_derived",
      "metadata": {
        "prior": 0.92,
        "prior_justification": "Self-report of methodology in the abstract: the authors state that the taxonomy was derived by analysing real-world implementations to extract structural patterns in context / tools / state. The cited GitHub link (aorwall/moatless-tools) anchors the claim in concrete open-source code. Small downward adjustment from 0.95 because, having only the abstract stub, we cannot verify how broad the surveyed corpus actually is.",
        "source": "artifacts/2604.03515-scaffold-taxonomy.md (abstract, sentence 2)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Structural patterns derived from real-world implementations",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "The taxonomy provides a treatment of **agentic memory** in coding agents -- how implementations represent, persist, and recall information across reasoning steps (e.g. scratchpads, episodic logs, retrieval over prior trajectories, long-term knowledge stores).",
      "content_hash": "73e0dfa8c2443f53467856b31f58d4dd60c72701b14c492c886562ae6d418111",
      "declaration_index": 4,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_03515_scaffold_taxonomy::keyword_agentic_memory",
      "label": "keyword_agentic_memory",
      "metadata": {
